    "transcript": "Clinician: Thank you for coming in today. I really appreciate you taking the time to speak with me about Eddie. I\u2019ll be asking a series of questions about his development, behaviour, and any concerns you might have. This will help us understand his strengths and challenges so that we can provide the right kind of support. If at any point you need me to clarify a question, please feel free to ask. Let\u2019s start with his early development. \n\nI. Early Development \n\nClinician: When did you first start noticing any concerns about Eddie\u2019s development? \n\nMum: I think it was around 18 months old. He wasn\u2019t speaking as much as other children his age, and he didn\u2019t seem to use gestures like pointing or waving. I also noticed he didn\u2019t respond to his name very often. It was subtle at first, and I thought maybe he was just a quiet baby. But as time went on, I started noticing how different he was compared to other children in the playgroup. At first, I wondered if maybe I was overthinking it. A lot of people reassured me that all children develop at their own pace. My mum said that my brother was a late talker, so maybe Eddie was just following that pattern. But deep down, I felt something was different. \n\nThen, when we were at the playground or toddler groups, I began noticing more things. Other children would point at things they found exciting or look back at their parents to see if they were watching, but Eddie never really did that. He didn\u2019t seem to notice if I was paying attention or not. If I pointed to something, like a bird in the sky or a dog passing by, he wouldn't follow my finger or react. He just carried on with whatever he was doing. I started watching other children his age, and I saw how much they engaged with their surroundings, whereas Eddie seemed to be in his own little world. \n\nClinician: Was he meeting his physical developmental milestones, such as crawling, walking, and sitting up? \n\nMum: Yes, mostly. He started crawling at around 10 months, which seemed typical, and he walked around 14 months, so there wasn\u2019t much concern there. But his babbling and speech development seemed much slower than expected. He didn\u2019t really engage in the usual baby talk you\u2019d expect at that age. When he did try to speak, it was often repetitive sounds rather than words, and he didn\u2019t mimic our speech the way other children did. I remember being reassured by friends and family that \u201cboys sometimes talk later,\u201d but I noticed he wasn\u2019t just late\u2014his whole way of communicating seemed different. \n\nFor example, when his older sister was that age, she would babble away and try to copy what we said. If we said \u201cdog,\u201d she would try to repeat it, even if it came out as \u201cda.\u201d But Eddie didn\u2019t do that. If he made sounds, they were often the same ones over and over, and they didn\u2019t seem connected to what was happening around him. He never really tried to copy words or sounds. Even when he did say something, it often didn\u2019t seem like he was using it to communicate\u2014he would repeat words he\u2019d heard, sometimes from TV shows, but not in a way that made sense in conversation. \n\nClinician: Did he show any early signs of interest in social interaction? \n\nMum: Not really. He seemed happy in his own world. He didn\u2019t look up when we called his name, and he rarely responded to people trying to engage him. If we played peekaboo, he wouldn\u2019t react much. I remember feeling concerned that he wasn\u2019t as interactive as the other toddlers in his playgroup. When we went to family gatherings, he would prefer to sit in a corner playing with a toy rather than interact with cousins or other children. At first, I thought he was just shy, but even when kids tried to play with him, he would ignore them or move away. \n\nI remember a specific incident at a friend\u2019s birthday party when he was about two years old. There were lots of children running around playing games, and I expected Eddie to join in at some point. But instead, he sat in a corner with a toy car, spinning the wheels over and over. He didn\u2019t seem upset or overwhelmed\u2014he just wasn\u2019t interested in the other children at all. Even when another child tried to take his car or get his attention, he didn\u2019t react. It was as if they weren\u2019t there. That was one of the moments when I really started to worry. \n\nClinician: Did he have any particular reactions to sensory experiences as a baby or toddler? \n\nMum: Yes, he was extremely sensitive to noise from a very young age. Everyday household sounds that most people wouldn\u2019t even notice could make him scream or cover his ears in distress. The vacuum cleaner was one of the worst triggers\u2014he would cry, scream, and sometimes even run out of the room if he heard it turn on. It was as if the sound physically hurt him. Similarly, sudden loud noises, like doors slamming or someone dropping a pan in the kitchen, would send him into a panic. He would flinch, cover his ears tightly, and sometimes burst into tears. It got to the point where we had to warn him before doing something loud, like using a hairdryer or blender, so he could prepare himself or leave the room. \n\nHis sensitivity wasn\u2019t just to noise\u2014he also struggled a lot with certain fabrics and textures on his skin. Some clothes would make him very upset, even if they felt soft to me. If I dressed him in something with a tag or a slightly rough fabric, he would immediately start pulling at it, whining or crying, and desperately trying to get it off. Sometimes, he would scratch at his arms or neck as if the fabric was unbearably irritating. I remember one time I bought him a new sweater that I thought he would like because it was warm and cozy, but as soon as I put it on him, he started sobbing and tugging at the sleeves, saying it was \u201ctoo itchy.\u201d He refused to wear socks with seams, and we often had to cut the tags out of his clothes to make them comfortable for him. \n\nHe also had a strong reaction to certain textures, particularly things that felt sticky or grainy. He absolutely refused to touch sand, play dough, or anything slimy. I remember taking him to the beach once, thinking he would love playing in the sand like his sister did. But as soon as he stepped onto it, he froze in place and started crying. He held his hands up in the air, visibly distressed, and refused to put them down. When a small gust of wind blew sand onto his skin, he shrieked and frantically tried to brush it off. No amount of encouragement or reassurance helped\u2014he just couldn\u2019t tolerate the sensation. Eventually, we had to carry him off the beach because he wouldn\u2019t walk on it. Even at home, if he got something sticky on his hands, like yogurt or glue from a craft project, he would become extremely anxious and demand that it be washed off immediately. If he couldn\u2019t get rid of the feeling fast enough, he would start crying and shaking his hands as if trying to fling it off. It was clear that these sensations were genuinely overwhelming for him, far beyond a simple dislike or discomfort. \n\n \n\nClinician: What about feeding? Did Eddie have any difficulties with eating or trying new foods? \n\nMum: He was always quite picky with food. Even as a baby, he would refuse certain textures, and as he got older, he would only eat very specific foods. He doesn\u2019t like anything mixed together, so if we give him a meal where different foods touch each other, he won\u2019t eat it. He also gets upset if a food looks slightly different from what he expects. If we buy a different brand of a food he likes, even if it tastes the same, he sometimes refuses to eat it. I used to think it was just a phase, but he hasn\u2019t really grown out of it. \n\nHe also prefers foods with a predictable texture\u2014crunchy foods are usually okay, but anything mushy or mixed is a challenge. We had so many struggles trying to introduce new foods. He would look at them suspiciously, sometimes refuse to even touch them, and if we encouraged him to take a bite, he would gag or spit it out. \n\nClinician: Were there any difficulties with sleeping patterns? \n\nMum: Yes, he\u2019s never been a good sleeper. From infancy, sleep was a major struggle. He would wake up multiple times during the night, sometimes crying inconsolably, other times just sitting awake in his cot, staring at the ceiling or playing with his fingers. Even as a toddler, it was rare for him to sleep through the night without at least one or two disturbances. Even now, he still has difficulty falling asleep, and he often wakes up much earlier than he should. He seems to have an internal clock that doesn\u2019t match up with the rest of the family\u2014he\u2019ll wake up at 4 or 5 AM, fully alert, while the rest of us are still exhausted. \n\nHe gets very distressed if his bedtime routine changes in any way. If we put him to bed even 15 minutes later than usual, he struggles to settle, sometimes tossing and turning for hours. If we forget to do something in his routine\u2014like skipping a specific lullaby or turning off the hallway light in a different order\u2014he becomes visibly anxious and has trouble relaxing. He seems to rely on the predictability of his bedtime routine to wind down. If something disrupts it, he can become restless, irritable, or even refuse to go to bed at all. \n\nThere are nights when he wakes up in the middle of the night and just stays awake for hours. Sometimes, he lies quietly in bed, staring at his hands or rolling a small toy between his fingers. Other times, he gets up and starts pacing around his room or whispering to himself. He doesn\u2019t always cry, but it\u2019s clear he\u2019s not getting the rest he needs. It\u2019s as if his brain is still too active to switch off. \n\nI remember how exhausting it was in those early years. We tried everything\u2014soothing music, bedtime stories, white noise machines, lavender sprays, different nightlights\u2014but nothing worked consistently. Some nights, he\u2019d fall asleep easily, but then wake up two hours later, wide awake as if it were morning. On particularly bad nights, he would be up for hours, and by the time he finally fell back asleep, it would be almost time for the rest of us to wake up. It was like his body clock was completely out of sync, and no matter what we tried, he just couldn\u2019t settle into a typical sleep pattern. \n\nWe also noticed that he has an unusual sensitivity to how his sleep environment feels. If his sheets have wrinkles, if his pajamas have seams that are even slightly uncomfortable, or if the temperature is too warm, he gets restless and struggles to sleep. He often prefers heavy blankets, even in summer, as if the pressure helps him feel more secure. We\u2019ve had to be very particular about his bedding, pajamas, and room conditions to minimize disruptions, but even then, sleep continues to be an ongoing challenge. \n\nClinician: How did he react to being comforted when he was upset? Did he seek comfort from you or others? \n\nMum: Not really. If he got hurt or was upset, he wouldn\u2019t run to me for a hug like other kids do. He would sometimes just sit and cry on his own. If I tried to comfort him, he would sometimes pull away or not really respond to it. It was difficult because I wanted to help him feel better, but he didn\u2019t seem to want physical reassurance. The only thing that sometimes helped was giving him his favorite toy\u2014he would hold it and calm down, but he didn\u2019t seek comfort from people the way his older sister did at that age. \n\nThere were times when I felt like I was failing him because I couldn\u2019t seem to comfort him the way I thought a parent should. But over time, I realized he just had different needs, and I had to find other ways to help him feel