other kids run around and play together, he\u2019ll sit off to the side, either playing with a toy, flipping through a book, or watching something on his tablet. He seems to prefer a quiet corner where he doesn\u2019t have to engage too much. If someone approaches him directly, he\u2019ll sometimes talk, but only on his terms. If he\u2019s in the middle of something, he might not even look up. \n\nEven in smaller groups, like when we\u2019re at home with close family, he often stays on the periphery of conversations. If we\u2019re all chatting at the dinner table, he\u2019ll either eat quietly or focus on something else, like lining up his food or playing with his utensils. When he does speak, it\u2019s usually about something specific he\u2019s interested in rather than responding to the ongoing conversation. \n\nIt\u2019s not that he dislikes people\u2014he just seems more comfortable as an observer rather than an active participant. He prefers one-on-one interactions, where the conversation is slower and more predictable. In larger groups, he tends to drift away, either physically by moving to a quieter spot, or mentally by tuning everything out. \n\nClinician: Does he use tone of voice appropriately? \n\nMum: Not always. Sometimes, his voice sounds flat, like he\u2019s just saying words without much emotion. Other times, he\u2019ll use a tone that doesn\u2019t match what he\u2019s saying\u2014he might sound excited when talking about something sad, or he might sound serious when he\u2019s trying to be funny. He doesn\u2019t seem to realise when his tone doesn\u2019t match the situation. Sometimes, he speaks in a sing-song voice, almost like he\u2019s imitating a cartoon character. He also doesn\u2019t always adjust his volume\u2014he might whisper when he should be speaking up, or he might talk too loudly in quiet places. \n\nClinician: Does Eddie understand jokes or sarcasm? \n\nMum: No, not really. If someone makes a joke, he usually doesn\u2019t react, or he 