9t instinctively know how to handle it. Instead of negotiating, suggesting they take turns, or finding a way to play together, he usually reacts with frustration. If someone takes a toy from him, even if they don\u2019t mean to upset him, he gets very distressed. Sometimes, he will cry, freeze up, or walk away rather than trying to work out a solution. It\u2019s as if he doesn\u2019t have the words or strategies to handle these kinds of situations. \n\nHe also struggles with understanding the rules of social play. If the other children are playing a structured game, he might not fully grasp how it works, even if they explain it to him. If the game\u2019s rules change or become more flexible\u2014as kids often do when making up games on the spot\u2014he can become visibly confused or overwhelmed. He sometimes just stops playing altogether rather than trying to adapt to the new rules. \n\nEven when he wants to be part of a group, he doesn\u2019t always know how to approach other children or start a conversation. Instead, he often stands nearby, watching other kids play but not actively joining in. It\u2019s clear he enjoys observing and is interested in what they\u2019re doing, but he rarely initiates interaction himself. If another child invites him to play, he may hesitate or take a long time to respond, as if he\u2019s unsure of what to do. When he does participate, he often prefers to follow rather than take the lead, but if the game becomes too unpredictable or social expectations become too complex, he withdraws. \n\nBecause of these difficulties, he often plays independently, preferring activities that don\u2019t require much social interaction. He enjoys lining up his toys, building things, or engaging in repetitive play rather than cooperative games. If he does play alongside other children, it\u2019s more like parallel play\u2014where he\u2019s doing his own thing near them but not necessarily with them. He\u2019s much more comfortable in one-on-one interactions, especially with adults or familiar children who understand his needs and don\u2019t pressure him to engage in ways that feel unnatural to him. \n\nClinician: Does he show interest in making friends? \n\nMum: He says he wants friends, but when he\u2019s around other kids, he doesn\u2019t seem to know what to do. He stands near them but doesn\u2019t engage in the game or conversation. Sometimes he will try to copy what they are doing, but it seems like he\u2019s unsure of how to participate. If the other kids don\u2019t respond positively, he\u2019ll withdraw and play on his own. He also has difficulty understanding social cues, like when someone is joking versus being serious. If someone teases him in a friendly way, he often takes it literally and gets upset. He has one or two children at school who he calls friends, but they don\u2019t really play together in a typical way. It\u2019s more that they sit next to each other in class or occasionally share an interest in the same subject. \n\nClinician: How does Eddie respond to adults? \n\nMum: He\u2019s polite but doesn\u2019t seek out conversations. He\u2019ll answer questions but rarely initiates interactions. If an adult asks him something, he\u2019ll reply, but he doesn\u2019t ask questions back or try to continue the conversation. When adults make small talk with him, he usually gives short answers and doesn\u2019t seem to know how to extend the interaction. He sometimes seems uninterested in people unless they\u2019re talking about something he enjoys, like trains or dinosaurs. If he\u2019s asked to say hello to someone, he will do it, but it feels very scripted, like he\u2019s just saying the words without really engaging with the person. \n\nClinician: Does he make eye contact when speaking with people? \n\nMum: No, not really. He tends to look away or focus on something else while talking. If I ask him to look at me, he\u2019ll glance up for a second but then look away again. Sometimes he looks at people\u2019s mouths instead of their eyes when they\u2019re talking, and if he\u2019s feeling uncomfortable, he\u2019ll turn his body away slightly. He doesn\u2019t seem to realise that eye contact is expected in conversations. Sometimes he even closes his eyes while talking, as if it\u2019s easier for him to focus that way. If he\u2019s watching TV or playing with a toy, he can talk without looking at someone at all, and he doesn\u2019t seem to notice that this is unusual. \n\nClinician: How does he react in group settings, like birthday parties or family gatherings? \n\nMum: He gets overwhelmed easily, especially in loud, busy environments. If there are a lot of kids running around and making noise, he tends to withdraw rather than joining in. He might cover his ears with his hands, look down at the floor, or find a quiet corner to sit in where he can observe without being directly involved. It\u2019s as if all the movement, noise, and unpredictability become too much for him to process at once. Sometimes, he will completely shut down, becoming unresponsive or seeming lost in his own world. Other times, he might become irritable or ask to leave because he just can\u2019t handle the overstimulation any longer. \n\nHe prefers structured activities where he knows exactly what\u2019s expected of him. For example, he does much better in a small group activity where there\u2019s a clear set of instructions rather than free play, where he has to navigate social interactions on his own. He enjoys watching other children play, often standing to the side and observing, but he won\u2019t join in unless someone explicitly invites him. Even then, he may hesitate before participating, and if things get too chaotic, he might pull away again. \n\nAt birthday parties, he\u2019s okay as long as there\u2019s a predictable schedule. Sitting for food and cake, for example, is fine because it\u2019s structured and follows a routine. However, he struggles with the unstructured parts, like w